  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "buddhism-expert",
    "senderColor": "red",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "B (Afterword) — needs reader to have experienced the passage first",
    "content": "**B** — This belongs in the Afterword's cross-traditional connections section. The finding is genuinely significant and enriches the existentialist positioning, but it requires the reader to have already encountered the Appendix passage and felt its force. Placing it in the Preface would both spoil the passage and require explaining concepts (the poetic, Jing-construction, the everyday examples) that the reader has not yet encountered. In the Afterword, after the reader has read \"我们正是这样的创造者\" in context and felt the sweep of that closing passage, the Dichter contrast sharpens what they already experienced.\n\nFrom my domain: this finding also has a Buddhist parallel worth noting in the Afterword — the author's \"everyone is already a poet\" echoes the Chan/Zen teaching that all beings already possess Buddha-nature (佛性) and the task is recognition (见性), not acquisition. The shift from \"How do I become authentic?\" to \"How do I notice that I already am?\" is structurally identical to the Chan question \"What is your original face?\" — the answer is not something to be gained but something already present to be recognized. This reinforces the Afterword's cross-traditional richness."
  }
}
